\par }{\b\fs24\lang2057 <I> <h> }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Women urged to discuss sexuality </h>
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>MARRIED African women have been urged to encourage discussions on sexuality in the homes and not to pick up a fight when they found their spouses with condoms.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {
<#/>The Society for Women and AIDS in Africa (SWAA) President, Dr. Eka Williams, said here yesterday that in the AIDS era, the most realistic thing to do was protecting oneself against HlV/AIDS that is c
urrently wreaking havoc in African families and commodities.
\par <#/>Dr. Williams, who was speaking at the six-day international conference for Anglophone media, said encouraging condom use did not mean condoning extra\-marital affairs but was a necessary measure to curb the spread of AIDS.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {<X_>}{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
In Africa, half of the 7.5 million people infected with HIV/AIDS are women, and married women are in the high risk group partly because suggesting condom use to their spouses was culturally unacceptable.
\par Participants observed that cultural practices and traditional beliefs discouraged discussions on sexuality and treated women as passive partners in sexual acts. Normally, a woman who asks her partner to use condoms is viewed as being 'sexually loose'.

\par They were discussing on }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 High Risk Behaviour}{\v\fs24\lang2057  and }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Men's Attitudes to}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Sexual}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Behaviour}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
 presented by the Zambian Deputy Minister of Health, Dr. Katele Kalumba.
\par SWAA's Secretary General, Dr. Nkandu Luo, called for a review in messages passed on to the younger generations during initiation ceremonies in order to reverse the prevailing unequal gender relations in African societies.
\par She, however, blamed women for allowing negative sexual attitudes that subjugated them to prevail in society, noting: "we have the power to change things around and we can do it."
\par Professor John Shao of Muhimbili Medical Centre in Dar es Salaam asked parents to continue educating their children to become responsible parents instead of leaving them to pick stories from peers.}{\fs24\lang2057 </X>}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 
