\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\b\fs24\lang2057 <I> <h> }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Guidelines on the law: Res judicata ends judicial decisions </h>
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>The law dictates that no issue should be raised again in the court of law which has been previously litigated and final <AmE/>judgment has been entered thereto.
\par <#/>This is what we call the principle of }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Res Judicate}{\fs24\lang2057 .
\par <#/>It is a doctrine which bars the subsequent litigation on matters which have been substantially and directly the subject of the litigation between all parties claiming under the subject matter.
\par <#/>The Civil Procedure Code 966, (CPC 1966), enacts this doctrine under section 9 thus: <quote_>
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<X_>}{\v 
"No court shall try any suit in which the matter directly and substantially in issue in a former suit between the same title in a court competent to try such subsequent suit or the suit in which such issue has been su
bsequently raised and has been heard and finally decided by such court." }{<7x><quote/>}{\v 
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\fs24\lang2057 Apparently it is a fact that the doctrine of Res Judicata is based on the principle that a decision once rendered by a competent <-/authourity> on a matter in issue betwe
en the parties after a full inquiry should not be permitted to be re-litigated.
\par <#/>In short, the doctrine needs to give finality to judicial decisions. <#/>And hence to prevent new decisions or investigations over the same matter.
\par <#/>This is intended to ensure that one and the same person is not harassed again and again in various proceedings upon the same subject matter.
\par <#/>The compliance with this position of the law is best found in Esta Mponda vVBakari Nahoda (1982) TLR 202.
\par <#/>In this case the appellant had petitioned at the Mnyambe Primary Court for a decree of divorce and lost.
\par <#/>She did not appeal against the decision but chose to file a fresh petition for a decree of divorce in the same Primary Court. <#/>She lost again.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>On appeal it was h
eld that since the substantial issue in the petition was whether the marriage had irreparably broken down, the appellant could not institute fresh proceedings on the basis of alleged matrimonial misconduct which could and ought to have formed part of the 
petition filed in 1976.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 
It was further held that it is in the interest of the State that there should be an end of litigation and it causes hardships for a party to be vexed twice for the same cause. <#/>Similarly in the case of Zuhura d/o Yusufu V. Jum
a Saidi (1969) HCD 193 the court found that the dispute was }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Res <-/Judcata>}{\fs24\lang2057 .
\par <#/>In this case the appellant in 1964 filed proceedings and obtained judgement against the respondent for 33 cows. }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>punct}{\fs24\lang2057  said to be part of her deceased husband's estate.
\par <#/>In 1968, the appellant filed the present proceedings, claiming 5 cows which she alleged had belonged to her husband.
\par <#/>She obtained judgement in the Primary Court, but this holding was reversed by the District Court on appeal.
\par <#/>Thereupon, she appealed to the High Court.
\par <#/>It was held that a plaintiff cannot, in the ordinary course of things, be permitted to file a series of suits in respect of the same cause of action.
\par <#/>Not only would this be an abuse of the process of the courts, but it might <-/proclude> a judgement-debtor from ever freeing himself from his obligation. <#/>To that effect, the appeal was dismissed.
\par <#/>In order for the doctrine of Res Judicata to apply, certain requirements should be fulfilled.
\par <#/>Firstly, there must exist two suits one finally and conclusively determined and another pending. <#/>This is a question of fact and law as well. <#/>For the defendant is required to produce evidence on this.
\par <#/>It is a question of fact because the defendant is dutybound to tender plead
ings and documentary evidence in court of the judgement of the previous suit. <#/>On the other hand, it is question of law because it is the duty of the court to determine whether or not the outcome of that previous proceedings constitute a judgement as d
efined by law. <#/>It is also the duty of the court to ascertain whether or not it was a suit.
\par <#/>It is on these factual situations that the court enables to resolve the issue whether the matter had really been finally and conclusively determined.
\par <#/>Secondly, both the suits must be before courts of competent jurisdiction. <#/>The term "court" is defined under the CPC 1966 to included "...the High Court of the Resident Magistrate or a District Court presided over by a civil magistrate...."
\par <#/>Clearly seen, the definition is restrictive since it does not embrace the Primary Court.
\par <#/>It suggests that Primary Courts are left outside the operation of the doctrine of Res Judicata.
\par <#/>However, the definition for the same as stipulated by Interpretation of Laws and General Clauses Act in effect covers the Primary Courts.
\par <#/>Thus the doctrine at issue <-/undobtedly> applies even in Primary Courts. <#/>It should be noted that Res Judicata applies notwithstanding that the judgement was wrongly reached.
\par <#/>What matters is that the court had got the jurisdiction to hear and determine the suit.
\par <#/>And thus to ascertain the question of whether or not the judgement was wrongly arrived at is to be dealt with an appeal or on revision. <#/>The High Court so stated in th
e case of  Tom Amiri Salim V. Firos Salehe Mohamed (1975) LRT N. 41 that: <quote_>
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {\v "The question whether the order is correct or erroneous has no bearing on the question whether it operates or not as Res judicat. That point could have been taken up on appe
al against that order...." }{<quote/>}{\v 
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\fs24\lang2057 It follows that in the absence of filing an appeal or applying for a revision of the decision, the said judgement will there be to stay, despite that it was wrongly entered.
\par <#/>The third requirement is that suit must be between the same parties or parties claiming under the same title.
\par <#/>Section 9 of the Code is clear about this requirement.
\par <#/>Explanation (IV) to this section elaborates the point. <#/>It states that:}{\b\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 <quote_>
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<X_>}{\v "Where persons litigate bona fide in 
respect of a public right or private right claimed in common for themselves and others, all persons interested in such right shall, for the purposes of this section, be deemed to claim under the persons so litigating." }{</X><quote/>}{\v 
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\fs24\lang2057 <-/Forthly>, it is requi
red that matters directly and substantially in issue between the parties in the pending suit must have been also directly and substantially in issue in the previous determined suit.
\par <#/>In short, it is meant that both must have been based on the same cause of action.
\par <#/>And it should be born in mind that the whole subject matter at issue in the subsequent suit must have been in issue in the previous suit.
\par <#/>Thus, it does not matter if the previous suit was wider than the subsequent one, provided the entire subsequent suit is swallowed.
\par <#/>With this respect }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>sense}{\fs24\lang2057 , it was argued in the case of Karsan V. Harnam (1953) 20 E.A.C.A. 74 that: <quote_>
\par <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 "Matter in issue does not mean any matter in issue in the suit, but has reference to the entire subject matter in controversy; it is not enough that one or some issue are in common.
\par The subject matter in the subsequent suit must be covered by the previous suit, not vice versa." }{\fs24\lang2057 </X><quote/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 Therefore, if the subsequent suit is wider than the previous one, then the doctrine of Res judicata cannot operate.
\par <#/>There are some exceptions to the operation of Res Judicata. <#/>As the above-cited case of Karsan shows, the doctrine of Res Judicata does not apply where the subsequent suit is wider than the previous suit.
\par <#/>Another exception to the doctrine is that if the new issue arises in the subsequent suit, the doctrine will not apply.
\par <#/>The reason behind is obvious. <#/>It is because the new issue had not been made a subject of inquiry to the previous suit.
\par <#/>Such kind of issues are collateral and incidental matters, which according to Bedford V. Cowtan and Sons Ltd. (1916) IKB 980, cannot act as Res Judicata. <#/>To quote Phillimore L.J. on page 989: <quote_>
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<X_>}{\v "But neither the judgement of a concurrent o
r exclusive jurisdiction is evidence of any matter which came collaterally in question, though within their jurisdiction, no of any matter incidentally cognizable, nor of any matter to be inferred argument from the judgement."}{ </X><quote/>}{\v 
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\fs24\lang2057 Another exceptional situation is where the previous judgement was entered by consent in which the court simply enters a compromise decree without taking evidence.
\par <#/>Such a judgement cannot operate as Res Judicata but rather it will be an estoppel.
\par <#/>Further the doctrine of Res Judicata will not <-/opeate> respect of ex parte judgements--against the plaintiff by virtue of Order 9 of the CPC 1966.
\par <#/>That is so because such judgement is entered on technicalities and not on merits of the case.
\par <#/>And so it is the case with judgements dismissing suits on grounds of time limit.
\par <#/>That is why Lyall J. in the case of Kahevhand V. Jan Mohamed (1919) 9 EAPIR 64, the appeal case where Res Judicata was pleaded in the second suit due to the fact that the first one was dismissed as it was time-barred, argued that }{\i\fs24\lang2057 
Res Judicata}{\fs24\lang2057  could not apply.
\par <#/>That is so because unless the matter directly and substantially in issue have been substantially heard and determined, they are not }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Res Judicata}{\fs24\lang2057 . <#/>To use the words of his lordship on Page 67: <quote_>
\par <X_>}{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 "In the former case the main issue was substantially the same but the only issue tried and determined was that of limitation barring the particular procedure adopted.
\par I am unable to see that the matter substantially in issue, vide, the question of respondent's indebtedness to the appellant has been either heard or determined"}{\b\fs24\lang2057 </X>}{\fs24\lang2057 <quote/>}{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 
\par }{\b\fs24\lang2057 On the same footing, Pickering J. remarked at Page 71 that: }{\fs24\lang2057 <quote_><X_>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 
\par }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 "It is familiar law that a statute which bars the remedy without extinguishing the debt is part of the }{\b\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Lex Fori}{\b\v\fs24\lang2057  only and a mere matter of procedure in that particular court."}{
\fs24\lang2057  </X><quote/>}{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 Thus it may be  to conclude that a dismissal of a suit being time barred is a dismissal on a preliminary point not to the facts of the case.
\par <#/>Acknowledgement of the debt, for example, can make the limitation period to run afresh.
\par <#/>However, as a point of remark, the case will not be exception to the operation of }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Res Judicata}{\fs24\lang2057  if the plaintiff appears and fails to adduce evidence.
\par <#/>In other words, the consequential judgement will here operate as Res Judicata because the plaintiff will be deemed to have submitted that he has no evidence to support his allegations.
\par <#/>This was substantially so stated in the case of }{\b\fs24\lang2057 Salem V. Hemeidan (1960) EA 92}{\fs24\lang2057  that:- <quote_> 
\par <X_>}{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 "The dismissal of a claim on account of the plaintiff's default to produce evidence to substantiate his case, has the same effect as dismissal found upon evidence and the subject matter of such a claim will be }{
\b\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Res Judicata}{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 .... }{\b\fs24\lang2057 </X>}{\fs24\lang2057 <quote/>}{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 In conclusion it can be argued that the doctrine of Res Judicata is intended to give finality to judicial decisions.
\par <#/>This in turn relieves defendants from being endlessly harassed.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>That is harassment brought by being compelled to appear and answer suits having the same <-/suhject> matter. </I>
