\par }{\b\fs24\lang2057 <I> <h> }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Guidelines on the law: Immunities given to diplomats </h>
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>The International Law among other things deals with diplomatic immunities and privileges.
\par <#/>These are supposed to be provided for by the host states to the foreign states (sending states) and their agents.
\par <#/>This is in compliance with the Vienna convention on Diplomatic Relations 1961.
\par <#/>Thus any country which signed the said Convention has to substantially reflect what is contained in the convention whenever enacting any local legislation touching on diplomatic immunities and privileges.
\par <#/>To ensure good relations and smooth-moving of functions by foreign embassies and their agents, Tanzania has enacted the Diplomatic and consular Immunities and Privileges Act 1986, No. 5.
\par <#/>The Act has greatly and substantially reflected what is contained in the above-cited Convention.
\par <#/>Above all the Act has made most of the relevant articles of this Convention schedule to it.
\par <#/>Just a remark, the schedule is part of the Act.
\par <#/>The Act specifies persons entitled to immunities and privileges. <#/>These include representatives in the United Republic of foreign sovereign powers; members
 of official staff of a diplomatic head of mission; members of the family or diplomatic staff of a chief representative; and also the members of the domestic staff of a head of mission.
\par <#/>Whereas the list of those entitled to immunities and privileges cover persons or institutions whom the Minister for Foreign Affairs is empowered to grant them immunities }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\fs24\lang2057 
 and privileges. <#/>According to Section 9 of the Act these are persons in the service of the government of a foreign sovereign power holdin
g an office involving the performance of duties substantially corresponding to those which in the case of a foreign sovereign power would be performed by a diplomatic agent.
\par <#/>Also a person for the time being recognised by the government of Tanzania as the head of mission in Tanzania of any state or province of a country represented here in Tanzania.
\par <#/>According to the Act No. 5 of 1986, a diplomat is immune from suit and legal process.
\par <#/>That he enjoys personal immunity from both civilian and criminal proceedings and above all, cannot be compelled to testify in court.
\par <#/>In this line of factual situation he is therefore immune from search, arrest, execution, and such like.
\par <#/>The premises of a mission are also inviolable - that no local authority may enter them without the consent of the head of the mission.
\par <#/>This is so substantially stated by Section 11 of the Act which provides for restriction of powers of entry in relation to consular posts.
\par <#/>It means that entry shall only be effected, apart
 from the consent of the head of the consular post or from the Minister for Foreign Affairs, where such entry is necessary for extinguishing fire which has or is reasonably believed to have broken out there on or on premises or place or for protecting the
 premises or place from acts done for the fighting purposes.
\par <#/>A police officer having reasonable cause to believe, that a crime, involving violence has been or is being or is about to be committed in the consular premises may enter therein.
\par <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>Lastly there shall be no restriction to enter consular premises where there exists any casement; contract or other private right. 
\par A diplomat is also covered by "All risk-insurance" in respect of any motor vehicle in this possession or use.
\par Financial <-/privila
ge> is also within the package entitled to a diplomat. This includes exemption from taxation. That is income, property and personal taxes. The said <-/privilage> further covers licences and registration fees paid under the Road Traffic Act 1972.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {\v Diplomats are also issued with dog licence, radio/wireless transmitter and arms licences without payment of fees.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\v\fs24\lang2057 Perhaps one may ask why a diplomat is immune from any criminal or civil process? 
\par Why does he enjoy a number of <-/privilages> which are not obtaining to the national of the country providing for the same? There are various reasons.
\par First, diplomatic immunities and privileges are intended to avoid conflicts between jurisdictions of the two states.
\par Let it be noted that members of the consular post and their activities in the embassy/high commission are primarily under the control and jurisdiction of the sending state.
\par The buildings occupied by such embassy being part of the receiving state notwithstanding.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {\v Secondly, bearing in mind the vital role played by the diplomat, exposing to criminal or civil liability would lessen his dignity and hence <-/embarass> him.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\v\fs24\lang2057 That is so because such immunities and privileges available to him are in honour of his sending state.
\par He just stands there as a representative of the said state. Fawcett in his book }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 The Law of Nations}{\v\fs24\lang2057  on page 67 observes:
\par "Immunity then is designed to protect the diplomatic functions, not to put the diplomat in a personally privileged position outside the law; the immunity is not his to invoke or waiv
e, it is strictly that of the state which sends him." Immunities also have the role to protect embassies from easy seizure or sacking.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {\v When seizure or sacking is given the room to happen it is <-/abvious> that no meaningful role or function of the diplomat will be effected.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\v\fs24\lang2057 "Such incidents in Indonesia and Macao, involving United States and British mission }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
, are paralleled by the seizure by the Albanian authorities in February 1964 of two Russian legation buildings, and by the activities of the "Red-guards" in Peking in 1966."
\par Thus it can be argued that the substantial reason behind diplomatic immunities is to ensure smooth running of diplomatic functions.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {\v And also to give security not only to <-_be><+_the> diplomats themselves but also to their consular premises. }{</X></I>
