\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <X_>}{\v\fs24 <h> }{\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>}{\v\fs24 Part One </h>}{\fs24 </X>
\par Voidable marriages are those which can be legally made void or capable of being annulled by the decree of the court upon request of the aggrieved party.
\par <#/>But in the absence of such a party to bring an action to court seeking the annulment, the marriage remains valid.
\par <#/>Section 40 of the Law of Marriage Act 1971, hereafter called the LMA 1971, exemplifies.
\par <#/>It states that: "A voidable marriage is for all purposes a valid marriage until it is annulled by a decree".
\par <#/>Thus, the option of the party aggrieved to set matrimonial <-/preceedings> in motion seeking a decree of annulment of their marriage to court is the determining factor as to whether the marriage should come to an end or to be existing.
\par <#/>It is apparently <-/abvious> that there are grounds which make a marriage to be voidable.
\par <#/>The LMA 1971 spells out those grounds.
\par <#/>According to Section 39 of the Act, the marriage is said to be voidable when at the time }{\b\v\fs24 <+_of>}{\v\fs24  }{\fs24 the marriage either party was incapable of consummating it.
\par <#/>Non-consummation is not only caused by incapacity but also due to wilful refusal of one party to consummate the marriage.
\par <#/>For one of the prerequisites to be met upon marriage is consummation.
\par <#/>That is having sexual intercourse between the husband and wife soon after they have married.
\par <#/>Emphasising on this Dr Lushington in D-E versus A-G (1845) 270 E.R. 1039 at page 1045 argued that: }{\fs24\lang2057 <quote_>}{\fs24 
\par <X_>}{\v\fs24 ... "In order to constitute the marriage bond between young persons, there must be the power, present or to come, of sexual intercourse.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {\v "Without that power neither of two principal 
ends of matrimony can be attained, namely a lawful indulgence of the passions to prevent licentiousness, and the procreation of children, according to the evident design of Divine Providence."}{ </X><quote/>}{\v 
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\fs24 Due to this position of the law, the existing inability or wilful refusal to consummate therefore, warrants the aggrieved party to institute an action in court for nullifying the marriage.

\par <#/>Thus non-consummation can exist due to either party's incapacity or wilful refusal to consummate.
\par <#/>The discussion intends to go into details of each.
\par <#/>To start with incapacity, there are possible causes which make a person unable to consummate.
\par <#/>For example, an impotence on the part of the husband to be able to have sexual intercourse.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang1031 <#/>Whereas body infirmity in the female body, frigidity and the like, to make penetration of male's genital organ impossible are the causes also.
\par \pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\fs24 <#/>To be elaborative, the case of A.v. B. (1932) 14 KLR 21 is referred to.
\par <#/>In this case, the husband sought a declaration of n
ullity in respect of the marriage celebrated between the parties on the ground of malformation, frigidity, impotence, or some other physical defect in the respondent, rendering her unable to consummate the marriage.
\par <#/>The trial judge dismissed the suit, 
finding that in view of the shortness of time during which the parties lived together it was impossible to presume that the respondent is impotent by reason of hysteria and that her refusal was probably due to youthfulness, innocence and nervousness.

\par <#/>The evidence showed that soon after the marriage, the parties stayed in an hotel for three days in Mombasa.
\par <#/>They went to Nairobi and stayed at the Avenue Hotel for two days, then went to Timau and spent ten days there with <-/frieds>.
\par <#/>At each of the places where the parties stopped, they shared the same room, and the petitioner attempted to consummate the marriage, but was rebuffed on each occasion.
\par <#/>He further testified that the respondent showed aversion from him and that he could not have consummated the marriage without using force.
\par <#/>Attempts were made to induce her to return to her husband, money provided for her passage, but such attempts were unavailing.
\par <#/>It was held that the facts on record justified the presumption of incapacity to consummate the marriage.
\par <#/>On the aspect of wilful refusal to consummate the marriage by either party the Dickinson v. Dickinson (1913) P.D. 198 enunciates it.
\par <#/>In this case the court, however, drew an inference of incapacity from the wilful and wrongful refusal of the wife to allow consummation in the trial. <#/>An appellate court held that:
\par Wilful and persistent refusal to allow any marital <-_intercourses><+_intercourse> is a sufficient ground for a decree of nullity of marriage.
\par <#/>Where, upon a pe
tition for nullity of marriage presented by the husband in good faith, it appeared that the consummation of the marriage had been prevented, after repeated attempts on his part, by the wilful, determined, <-/stead fast> refusal of the wife, likely to be, 
persisted in, ... this constituted a valid and sufficient ground for annulling the marriage. ...
