\par }{\fs24 <h> Part Two </h>
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {THIS last part of the discussion is the continuation of the grounds which make the marriage voidable.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {<#/>}{\fs24 Thereafter we shall discuss the effects of the decree of annulment of a voidable marriage.
\par <#/>The marriage is also voidable when at the time of the marriage it is proved that the wife is pregnant by the third party.
\par <#/>In other words, that the wife, as per Section 39 (a) (iv) of the LMA 1971, was made pregnant by some person other than the husband.
\par <#/>This occurs that before the parties marry, the wife might have had sexual intercourse with other men than the husband.
\par <#/>And that either with or without her knowledge she conceived.
\par <#/>The husband, without knowledge of the <-/pregnance> he marries her.
\par <#/>When that is the case the law opens the door for the husband to petition for a decree of annulling the marriage.
\par <#/>The husband should, however submit the application in court as soon as possible.
\par <#/>Above all, upon learning that his wife is already pregnant with the third party before they got married, he should not have sexual intercourse with her any more, pending the order of the court.
\par <#/>A typical example to illustrate the above is an English case of Stocker versus Stocker (1966) 2 All E.R. 147.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang1031 <#/>This was a petition by the husband for a decree of nul
lity on the grounds that at the time of the marriage the wife was pregnant by some person other than the husband and was subject to recurrent attacks of epilepsy.
\par \pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\fs24 <#/>The parties met on April 15,1965, and within a fortnight of meeting were having regular sexual intercourse together.
\par <#/>The husband took the precaution of wearing a contraceptive sheath on all occasions.
\par <#/>He thought that perhaps both by what she said and by her own general demeanour to intercourse that he was not the first man whom she had known carnally, but he was not very critical of her in that respect.
\par <#/>Towards the end of June, 1965, the wife moved to another part of the country.
\par <#/>The parties kept in touch, mostly by letter, and at about that time the wife told the husband that s
he had missed a period and suspected that she was pregnant. <#/>The husband genuinely thought that he was the father of the expected child, and on that assumption he thought it proper to marry her in due course.
\par <#/>The marriage took place on August 5, 196
5. <#/>With regard to the allegation of epilepsy, the trial judge found as a fact that, at the time of the marriage the wife was suffering from recurrent attacks of epilepsy, but that at that time the husband was ignorant of that fact.
\par <#/>Karminski, J. held and I quote: }{\fs24\lang2057 <quote_><X_>}{\v\fs24 
"According to Section 9(1) of the Matrimonial Causes Act 1965, 'the Court has to be satisfied, that at the time of the marriage, the husband was ignorant of the fact, that his wife was pregnant by another man.
\par "I am perfectly satisfied that the husband was. Accordingly the decree of nullity issued".}{\fs24 </X>}{\fs24\lang2057 <quote/>}{\fs24 
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>It is sometimes difficulty for the husband to prove that the wife's pregnancy is by the third party.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {<#/>}{\fs24 This occurs especially in instances where he had carnally known her even before the marriage.
\par <#/>And it may appear that since the wife had sexual intercourse with other men, she may even fail to pinpoint the specific man with whom she conceived.
\par <#/>To that effect, though she may be sure that it is not the husband who impregnated her, and the fact that the period in which she conceived the husband also had carnally known her, she after marriage names him as the responsible one for the pregnancy.

\par <#/>It is difficult to prove that he is not responsible on the existing presumption of legitimacy.
\par <#/>The same was experienced in the case of W.V.W. (No.4) (1963) 2 All E.R.841.
\par <#/>In this case the husband brought an application in a nullity suit for an order requiring the wife and her child to submit to a blood test.
\par <#/>The ground for the petition for nullity of marriage is that at the time of the marriage the wife was pregnant by another person than the husband.
\par <#/>The husband, however, admitted that he himself had sexual intercourse with the wife before marriage.
\par <#/>He alleged that the wife also had sexual intercourse with another man or men.
\par <#/>Dismissing the appeal, Willmer, L.J. had this to say:}{\fs24\lang2057  <quote_>}{\fs24 
\par }{\b\fs24 <X_>}{\b\v\fs24 "The point has been made that in such a case the task of a petitioner in proving his case is an extremely difficult one, bearing in mind the presumption of legitimacy.
\par This husband accordingly asked for an order for a blood test, on the ground or basis that otherwise it will be practically impossible for him to prove his case.
\par "Accordingly this appeal should be dismissed.}{\fs24\lang2057  </X><quote/>}{\b\v\fs24 
\par }{\fs24 <#/>Commonly noted, most of wives married while they are pregnant by other persons than their husbands conceal this fact to them.
\par <#/>The reasons are obvious.
\par <#/>They know that they would not have been married had the husbands learned about this reality.
\par <#/>Also, others may be denied by those who impregnated them.
\par <#/>So when they get offers of marriage from men who are not aware of the fact and who can easily be moved to believe that they are the ones responsible for the said pregnancies after a short stay in the marriage, they stick to them and hide the truth.

\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>However, let it be noted that the position of the law remains as it is that the marriage will still be voidable and not otherwise despite the existing concealment on the part of the wife.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {<#/>}{\fs24 To get the gist of the <-/aforegoing> the case of Moss v. Moss (1897) P.263 is relevant.
\par <#/>In this case, the husband brought the suit for nullity of marriage on the ground of fraud on the part of the respondent.
\par <#/>The petitioner on the very day of the marriage had suspicions on the condition of the respondent.
