\par }{\b\fs24\lang2057 <I> <h> <#/>When is the court functus officio under the law? </h>
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>A TRIAL court has virtually no power to change its order or decision it has made which has the effect of finally disposing of the  matter.
\par <#/>When the court makes an order or decision which in essence puts off the matter it is said to become FUNCTUS OFFICIO.
\par <#/>Let us have a look at cases relating to plea taking. <#/>It is an established principle both in law and practice that when an accused pers
on is charged with an offence, the charge has got to be read over and its facts explained to him in the language he can understand.
\par <#/>He should tell the court in clear and understandable words whether he admits to have committed the offence or not.
\par <#/>When the accused person pleads guilty and the court is fully satisfied that such plea is unequivocal then it enters conviction and finally sentences him accordingly.
\par <#/>It should be noted here that when an accused person pleads guilty in subordinates courts he forfeits his right to appeal against conviction.
\par <#/>However, the situation is }{\i\fs24\lang2057 vice versa}{\fs24\lang2057  for conviction on plea of guilty that originates from the High Court.
\par <#/>The question which is worthy asking }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\fs24\lang2057  is, \rdblquote when does the trial court becomes }{\i\fs24\lang2057 functus officio}{\fs24\lang2057  regarding conviction and sentence?"
\par <#/>Prior to 1967 or so as evidenced by the case of Maumba vs Republik 1966 E.A. the legal position was that once the court had accused plea of guilty could change it but rather proceed to impose the appropriate sentence thereto.
\par <#/><-/Todate> the legal position is that an accused person can change his plea from that of guilty to that of not guilty or vice versa provided that such change is made any time sentence has been meted out.
\par <#/>In the case of Joseph Ogola vs Republic 2 EACA 171, the court had this to say: <quote_>
\par <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 "A trial cannot accept a change of plea once it has entered conviction and passed sentence because such court becomes }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 functus}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 officio,}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
 but the court is not entered conviction following an }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 functus officio}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
 until it has made an order finally disposing of the matter, in other words, a trial court may allow an accused to change his plea to that of not guilty at any time before sentence is passed".}{\fs24\lang2057 </X><quote/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 In Kamundi vs Republic 1973 E.A. 540, the appellant together with four others were convicted on a purported plea of guilty to a charge of robbery with violence.
\par <#/>The charge was read and facts were explained to the appellants.
\par <#/>They all pleaded guilty. <#/>The trial Magistrate convicted them as charged.
\par <#/>The case was adjourned for a while to allow the prosecution to produce of the accused persons.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>When the trial resumed the appellant was able to secure services of an advocate who strongly submitted that the appellant's plea was equivocal.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 
The counsel's submission was rejected by the learned trial magistrate as he was of the settled view the accused pleas were unequivocal and that the court had no power to quash its own decision and therefore completely refused to allow th
e appellant to change his plea to that of not guilty.
\par <#/>When the case came on appeal the court held strongly that the trial court was not }{\i\fs24\lang2057 functus officio}{\fs24\lang2057  it could have changed the appellant's plea.
\par <#/>The court had this to say at page 545 of the aforementioned case: <quote_><X_>"}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
The whole purpose and intention of the criminal procedure.... to lay down provisions and procedures to see justice is done, and justice cannot be effected if the plea is entered as a result of ignorance or misunderstanding.}{\fs24\lang2057  </X><quote/>}{
\v\fs24\lang2057 
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 "The court must have a judicial discretion to allow a change of plea before it has disposed of the case. 
\par "It is common practice to allow the accused during the course of trial to change his plea of not guilty to that of guilty. 
\par "We see no reason why the trial court should not have similar power to change a plea of guilty to that of not guilty". }{\fs24\lang2057 </X>
\par In the recent case of Rajabu Ramadhani vs Republic 1980 TLR 50.
\par <#/>The appellant was facing a charge of cattle theft. <#/>When charge and facts were read and explained to him he just said they were correct.
\par <#/>However, in mitigation the accused was heard saying:
\par "I was invited by some people who told me that the cow was theirs".
\par <#/>The trial court neglected the mitigation and proceeded with sentence.
\par <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>On appeal the court held that the words by the appellant in mitigation amounted to a recantation of his earlier plea and further that the court was not }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 functus officio}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
 as it had not passed sentence when the accused recanted his plea.
\par In general the court in this case held two important things, that is, when an accused person pleads guilty but in mitigation exculpates himself this amounts to recantation of his earlier plea; and that the court becomes }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 
functus officio}{\v\fs24\lang2057  when it disposes of a case by a verdict of guilty or by passing sentence or making some orders finally disposing of the case.
\par It can thus be said as a concluding remark that the accused's right to change his plea of not guilty to guilty is open before full <-/trialbegins> .
\par The period when the right of the accused to change plea survives, the court is never }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 functus officio}{\v\fs24\lang2057 .
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {\v However, the accused request to change his plea of not guilty to guilty is open before full <-/trialbegins>.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\v\fs24\lang2057 The period when the right of the accused to change plea survive, the court is never functus officio }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\v\fs24\lang2057 . }{\fs24\lang2057 </X></I>

