\par <I> <h> }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Guidelines on the law: Musicians advised on copyright law </h>
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>For those who did not chance to read the first part of this article, let them know that in the first part we discussed and explained what copyright is.
\par }\pard\plain \s17\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang1031 {\lang2057 <#/>We said that Copyright denotes an exclusive right to authorise the reproduction of an artistic or literal work for commercial purpose.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\fs24\lang2057 <#/>We further said that the law of Copyright generally deals with protection of those works against reproduction by persons who are not the real inventors of them.
\par <#/>When one talks of the owner of a Copyright, it means a person who has an exclusive right on a Copyright work as recognised by law. <#/>Section 11(1) of the Copyright Act provides that:
\par "The Copyright on works which are eligible for copyright under the Act shall be initially vested in the author."
\par <#/>Under the provision the word author denotes a person who, with his skill and labour, or probably his capital, made the work in question.
\par <#/>Therefore at first the ownership of a work vests in the person who actually made it.
\par <#/>If it is a book the copyright vests in the person who wrote it.
\par <#/>If it is a musical work the right vests on a person who composed it.
\par <#/>This is the general position as far as ownership of copyright is concerned.
\par <#/>There are situations in which <-/sometime> the right on a work does not vest in a person who is actually the maker of it.
\par <#/>Although the ownership of Copyright on a work is first vested on the author, if the work in question is made under a contract of service, then the ownership vests on the employer of the author.
\par <#/>This is provided under Section 11(1) (i) of the Copyright Act. <#/>But such a work shall be owned by employer if, and only if, the employee made it in the course of his employment.
\par <#/>That is for example, a musician composes a piece of music during his <-/leissure> time at home, there is no way the owner of his orchestra can claim copyright ownership on the music unless the employee decides so.
\par <#/>One question which is controversial at this juncture is when a person is said to be acting in the course of his employment.
\par <#/>An employee is said to be acting in the course of his employment when he is under the control of his employer.
\par <#/>It is when he performs his duty in accordance and under the terms of the contract of service, in the premises of his employer or in the premises provided or directed by his employer.
\par <#/>Two years ago there arose an issue between two orchestras both based in Dar es Salaam city.
\par <#/>The issue which still exists in many people's minds is who should be the owner of a musical work titled "<ea_>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 Wenye Nyumba Msinyanyase Wapangaji<ea/>}{\fs24\lang2057 ".
\par <#/>Initially this work was composed by one musician known as Ramadhani Kingute, alias Kingute System.
\par <#/>He composed it when he was an employee of Orchestra DDC Mlimani Park.
\par <#/>He performed the work with his fellow employees of the same orchestra several times in different dancing halls.
\par <#/>Then the composer, Kingute, shifted to the Orchestra Bicco Stars.
\par <#/>He shifted before the work was recorded by his former Orchestra with RTD.
\par <#/>Then he decided to perform the same music with his new Orchestra.
\par <#/>Later the song was recorded to RTD by both orchestras with slight variations.
\par <#/>I am not sure which orchestra recorded the song first. <#/>Now the issue was who could claim Copyright ownership on that work.
\par <#/>If the music was composed by Mr. Kingute in his course of employment by Orchestra DDC, then in law the music belongs to Orchestra DDC as the employer of Kingute.
\par <#/>This is in accordance with the provision of Section 11(1) (i) of the Copyright Act.
\par <#/>But this also will depend much on the terms of contract under which Kingute was employed.
\par <#/>Having no terms under the contract which provided contrary to what the law provides, and taking into account that Kingute composed the work and used DDC's instruments to test it with other employees of DDC, in 
their normal practice days and hours, then the work totally belongs to the DDC Mlimani Park Orchestra.
\par <#/>This is because Kingute composed the work as his duty as an employed musician.
\par <#/>On the contrary, if the work was composed by Kingute himself, usin
g his own brain and, if the music was rehearsed by Kingute with his colleagues not within their normal course of employment, with the intention that they were performing a work of Kingute, then the work would belong to Kingute and he would be having exclu
sive Copyright on it.
\par <#/><-/May be> it is here where our musicians should know that despite of the law to confer copyright on their employers, yet there is a room for them to have some rights on their works.
\par <#/>The only thing is that, their rights can be included in their written contract of employment.
\par <#/>It is important to remind you one thing at this stage while we have been discussing the issue in the song titled <ea_>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 Wenye nyumba Msinyanyase Wapangaji<ea/>}{\fs24\lang2057 ," we should not forget what was discussed in
 the first part of this article.
\par <#/>In the first part of the article it was pointed out that under Section 3(2) (b) a work shall not be eligible for copyright protection unless it is reduced into some permanent tangible form.
\par <#/>Therefore taking into account all what have been discussed above, the ownership of the song in question, depends on who was the first to reduce it into a permanent tangible form as between the two orchestras.
\par <#/>When Kingute performed the work with his new orchestra, Bicco Stars, the music was not recorded anywhere then that act by Kingute would not amount to a breach of Copyright.
\par <#/>This is because the song just existed in the heads of DDC musicians, nothing like a disk or a cassette existed hence rendering the song eligible for copyright.
\par <#/>But if when the song was composed by Kingute and recorded in the name of DDC Mlimani Park Orchestra, then the music would be eligible for Copyright.
\par <#/>Here the song will be eligible because it would be already existing in a permanent form; a form which can be reproduced into another permanent form for sale.
\par <#/>Thus the act of Bicco Stars to record the same with RTD would amount to a breach of Copyright.
\par <#/>In short therefore, the ownership of this song actually depends on who was the inventor of it.
\par <#/>It will depend on what circumstances the inventor was labouring - as an employee or not.
\par <#/>It further depends on the nature of the contract of employment between Kingute and DDC Mlimani Park.
\par <#/>Further this will depend on the answer to the question as to who was the first person to record the song.
\par <#/>The Copyright for works which are eligible for copyright made by or under the direction or control of the Government or international bodies or other organizations, vests initially in the government or such international body or organization.
\par <#/>This is provided under Section 6 of the Copyright Act.
\par <#/>A good example of such works are songs like "}{\i\fs24\lang2057 Chama Chetu Cha Mapinduzi Chajenga Nchi}{\fs24\lang2057 "; the National Anthem and the like.
\par <#/>These songs belong to the CCM and the Government, respectively.
\par <#/>Before we come to the end of this article, let me put forward one suggestion to our music composers.
\par <#/>When any musician is entering into a contract of employment with any holder of an orchestra, that must be reduced in writing.
\par <#/>In such a documented contract, each part must state all what he wishes under the law of Copyright. </I>
