\par }{\b\fs24\lang2057 <I> <h> <#/>Guidelines on the law: Delayed court cases: who is to be blamed? </h>
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>IN OLD days African administration of justice was composite.
\par <#/>Wherever a dispute arose, there were no separate judicial institutions like those we have now.
\par <#/>Instead members of society in which the disputants belonged, especially elders, met, <-_summon><+_summoned> the parties, <-_make><+_made> inquiries into the dispute and the society at large could reach at a decision.
\par <#/>There were no hard and fast rules of procedure which had to be followed like those we have in our courts today. <#/>What prevailed was democracy.
\par <#/>That means each member of the society was free to give his views on a given dispute for settlement.
\par <#/>In most African societies women were not allowed in decision-making positions.
\par <#/>All in all what was common in all those societies is that a decision was reached by the <-/concensus> of all participants. <#/>And it was binding to both parties.
\par <#/>This system was easy and quick to administer justice.
\par <#/>To the people of those old days this system was the most appropriate because each society could solve disputes according to its prevailing cultures.
\par <#/>The aim of dispute settlement always was to reconcile the disputants.
\par <#/>At the end of the hearing disputants became friendly again.
\par <#/>In most cases at the end the disputants shook hands and sank their differences by taking a traditional brew.
\par <#/>That is not the case in our courts today. <#/>These days before you take your case to court you must ask yourself many questions.
\par <#/>First of all you must be sure of whether you will have enough time to sacrifice in court before your case can be determined.
\par <#/>You must also ask yourself whether you have enough money to engage an advocate to defend you.
\par <#/>If you are not ready to engage an advocate you must be confident and conversant with all the rules applicable in courts.
\par <#/>This leads us to the conclusion that today justice is more expensive than it was before.
\par <#/>Mostly it is only the <-/richman> who are able to get their rights in court.
