\par <#/>To me it is not always true that magistrates or judge are the only causes of delays in hearing cases in our courts.
\par <#/>One has to know that before a case comes to an end there are so many steps and procedures which have to be followed.
\par <#/>When a case is opened in court, whether it is a criminal or a civil case, the magistrate or the judge must ensure that justice is done from the beginning to the end.
\par <#/>It is after giving each party a fair hearing that the magistrate reaches at a particular decision, ruling or a judgement.
\par <#/>Whenever a magistrate adjourns case he sets another hearing date after suggestions from both parties as to what will be the convenient date for the two sides and to the court itself.
\par <#/>When a suspect is arrested he is first taken to the police office.
\par <#/>The police, on behalf of the republic, draws a charge against the suspect. <#/>Sometimes the police may <-/deliverately> delay preparation of a charge.
\par <#/>So you find a person being held at a police station for three or four days before being taken to court.
\par <#/>But a charge is in most cases hardly one page.
\par <#/>It can be prepared within half an hour.
\par <#/>After charging the <-/accussed> he is taken to court where on first appearance he will be asked to enter his plea.
\par <#/>When the <-/accussed> denies the facts of the charge the story starts as follows:
\par First you hear from the <-/posecutor> who might say, "please your honour, investigations are not complete so I pray for another mentioning date."
