\par "Please your honour, the file of this case is still with <ea_>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Ngazi za juu<ea/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057  (top-officials) for more investigations.
\par "So I pray for another mentioning date." This story may be repeated for three or four times.
\par Under such circumstances, we cannot blame the judge or magistrate for the delay in hearing the case.
\par Then comes the day when the prosecutor says "your honour investigations are complete, so I pray for a hearing date."
\par Then the magistrate adjourns the case and sets a date for hearing to start.
\par Again, before the magistrate records the hearing date you hear another learned brother saying "please your honour I am the advocate for the accused.
\par "On the proposed date I will be defending another case in the High Court before judge ....
\par "So <-_many><+_may> your honour set another date ahead." Then the magistrate sets another date four days later than the previous one.
\par When the proposed date comes, the prosecutor is asked to call his witnesses. The first witness comes and gives his evidence.
\par Sometimes evidence of one witness might be too long.
\par Therefore the magistrate may adjourn the case to proceed with the same witness on another day.
\par When hearing continues on the next day you may hear the prosecutor saying "please your honour my witness is very sick therefore he could not manage to appear today. I pray for adjournment."
\par Again before the magistrate proposes another hearing date to continue with the evidence of the first prosecution witness, you hear the advocate for the accused saying "your honour, for the coming three weeks I will be on safari to Mwanza, where I wi
ll be defending two cases.
